<h2 id="section-top">Pain Management</h2>
</div>
<div class="col four-sm">
</div>
<div class="col three-sm" id="ctl00_ctl00_ctl00_PlaceHolderMain_contentColumn1">
<div class="box">
<p class="module">
        This Department is managed by  
        <a href="/Services/Trusts/Overview/DefaultView.aspx?id=1664">Dartford and Gravesham NHS Trust</a>
</p>
<div class="panel">
<div class="panel-content">
<div class="pad clear">
<div class="service-locations clear">
<div class="panel edit-box">
<div class="panel-content">
<div class="pad clear">
<p class="address"><br/>01322 428100</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="panel">
<div class="panel-content">
<div class="pad clear">
<div id="imageContenta18270016e7749dca45b6f3119209bca">
<div class="profile-pic">
<img alt="Pain Management" border="0" id="ctl00_ctl00_ctl00_PlaceHolderMain_column1Content_column1Content_SummaryAndPhotoModule_PhotoView_DisplayImage" src="/Services/UserControls/UploadHandlers/MediaServerHandler.ashx?id=49816"/>
</div>
</div>
<p>Acute Pain Services (APS) are an essential service in hospitals that perform major surgery. Decisions regarding the management of acute pain following surgery or trauma are generally made by the anaesthetist.</p>
<p>The APS is consultant led, with a full time Acute Pain Clinical Nurse Specailist. Options for the management of post-operative pain are usually discussed in consultation with the patient at the pre-admission visit prior to surgery.</p>
<p> </p>
<p>APS is responsible for providing safe and effective acute pain management by:</p>
<ul class="unIndentedList">
<li>Managing all patients with epidural, regional, or patient controlled analgesia or continuous analgesic infusions.</li>
<li>Reviewing all patients referred experiencing acute pain.</li>
<li>Developing evidenced based education programs for nursing, medical and allied health staff.</li>
<li>Developing policies and procedures for analgesic therapy.</li>
<li>Collecting and analyzing APS data to ensure the quality and safety of patient care.</li>
</ul>
<p> </p>
<p>The Acute Pain Team is organised to meet the patient's needs. This may involve professionals from the following groups: specialist consultants, specialist nurses and physiotherapists.</p>
<p>The Acute Pain Sister's role is to educate nurses, doctors and patients about pain management. Generally, patients are seen post-operatively by the sister and anaesthetist to ensure that the pain relief is adequate for their pain. This means that the patient will be able to cough, deep breathe and move relatively easily to help their recovery.</p></div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="panel name-thingsshouldknowmodule">
<div class="panel-content">
<div class="pad clear">
<h3>Things you should know</h3>
<p>Dartford and Gravesham NHS Trust runs this service at Darent Valley Hospital, Queen Mary's Hospital and Erith &amp; District Hospital.</p>
</div>
